This quote from the late Terry Pratchett captures the importance of the writer’s first draft as a way of starting the process of creating a story or book. Before you can share your story with readers, you must learn what the story is in the first place.

Then, through a process of refinement, you turn your story into the version that’s shared with the world. At Elite Authors, we’ve helped many authors take their first-draft version of a story and turn it into something ready to be shared.

But it always starts with the author and their work to figure out the story behind their story. What story do you want to tell yourself?

His heart was beating fast. He had not returned to the Clinic since the operation...
Something was wrong since then: in the file of memories that had been implanted after the accident, there was one that haunted her. A recurring memory that woke her up at night, that she did not assimilate as her own and that no one around her recognized. A piece that did not fit the puzzle...
.
.
Su corazón latía aceleradamente. No había vuelto a la Clínica desde la operación... 
Algo no iba bien desde entonces: en el fichero de recuerdos que le habían implantado trás el accidente, había uno que la obsesionaba. Un recuerdo recurrente que la despertaba por las noches, que no asimilaba como propio y que nadie de su entorno reconocía. Una pieza que no encajaba en el puzzle...
.
.
